[src:carbon-cycle/2019-in-climate-change] This article documents events, research findings, scientific and technological advances, and human actions to measure, predict, mitigate, and adapt to the effects of global warming and climate change—during the year 2019.
[src:carbon-cycle/2019-in-climate-change] National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA).
[src:carbon-cycle/2020-in-climate-change] This article documents events, research findings, scientific and technological advances, and human actions to measure, predict, mitigate, and adapt to the effects of global warming and climate change—during the year 2020.
[src:carbon-cycle/2021-in-climate-change] This article documents events, research findings, scientific and technological advances, and human actions to measure, predict, mitigate, and adapt to the effects of global warming and climate change—during the year 2021.
[src:carbon-cycle/2021-in-climate-change] among climate experts (2010–2015) reflect that the level of scientific consensus correlates with expertise in climate science.
[src:carbon-cycle/2021-in-climate-change] and a 2021 study concluded that consensus exceeded 99%.
[src:carbon-cycle/2021-in-climate-change] Another 2021 study found that 98.7% of climate experts indicated that the Earth is getting warmer mostly because of human activity.
[src:carbon-cycle/2022-in-climate-change] This article documents events, research findings, scientific and technological advances, and human actions to measure, predict, mitigate, and adapt to the effects of global warming and climate change—during the year 2022.
[src:carbon-cycle/2022-in-climate-change] A 2022 study found that the public substantially underestimates the degree of scientific consensus that humans are causing climate change.
[src:carbon-cycle/2022-in-climate-change] found scientific consensus to range from 98.7–100%.
[src:carbon-cycle/2022-in-climate-change] Research found that 80–90% of Americans underestimate the prevalence of support for major climate change mitigation policies and climate concern.
[src:carbon-cycle/2022-in-climate-change] While 66–80% Americans support these policies, Americans estimate the prevalence to be 37–43%.
[src:carbon-cycle/2022-in-climate-change] National political divides on the seriousness of climate change consistently correlate with political ideology, with right-wing opinion being more negative.
[src:carbon-cycle/2023-in-climate-change] This article documents events, research findings, scientific and technological advances, and human actions to measure, predict, mitigate, and adapt to the effects of global warming and climate change—during the year 2023.
[src:carbon-cycle/2024-in-climate-change] This article documents events, research findings, scientific and technological advances, and human actions to measure, predict, mitigate, and adapt to the effects of global warming and climate change—during the year 2024.
[src:carbon-cycle/2024-in-climate-change] paper to conclude that climate change's increase of water temperatures intensified peak wind speeds in all eleven 2024 Atlantic hurricanes.
[src:carbon-cycle/2024-in-climate-change] Scientists in the field of extreme event attribution have concluded that in virtually all countries and territories around the world in a year-long period beginning in May 2024, human-caused global warming has increased the number of days of extreme heat events over long-term norms.
[src:carbon-cycle/2024-in-climate-change] As a source of electric power in the EU, renewables overtook fossil fuels by 2020, and solar and wind together exceeded fossil fuels by 2025.
[src:carbon-cycle/2024-in-climate-change] The share of electricity coming from renewable sources continues to vary widely among European nations.
[src:carbon-cycle/2024-in-climate-change] A few countries generate more electricity from renewables than is consumed in total.
